{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641007"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:21:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17853"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17853"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78561"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10567"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-12-22T04:57:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:02:23+09:30","updatedAction":"updated","acceptedAt":"2024-12-22T05:00:36+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":null},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17853"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24637"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63903"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78561"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInsulin is released after meals to regulate glucose metabolism. One of its key functions is to promote the storage of glucose as glycogen in liver and muscle tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the insulin signalling pathway that promotes glycogen synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Akt activates GSK3b, an activator of glycogen synthase","Akt inactivates GSK3b, an activator of glycogen synthase","Akt activates GSK3b, an inhibitor of glycogen synthase","Akt inactivates GSK3b, an inhibitor of glycogen synthase","GSK3b activates Akt, an activator of glycogen synthase"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInsulin signalling leads to the activation of \u003Cstrong\u003EAkt\u003C/strong\u003E, which then \u003Cstrong\u003Einactivates GSK3b\u003C/strong\u003E. Since GSK3b normally inhibits glycogen synthase, its inactivation allows glycogen synthase to become active and promote glycogen synthesis. This pathway is crucial for glucose storage after meals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAkt activates GSK3b, an activator of glycogen synthase\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect on two counts: GSK3b is an inhibitor (not activator) of glycogen synthase, and Akt inactivates (not activates) GSK3b\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAkt inactivates GSK3b, an activator of glycogen synthase\u003C/strong\u003E - While Akt does inactivate GSK3b, GSK3b is an inhibitor, not an activator of glycogen synthase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAkt activates GSK3b, an inhibitor of glycogen synthase\u003C/strong\u003E - Akt inactivates, rather than activates, GSK3b\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGSK3b activates Akt, an activator of glycogen synthase\u003C/strong\u003E - The sequence is reversed: Akt acts upstream to regulate GSK3b, not the other way around\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Insulin promotes glycogen synthesis by inactivating glycogen synthase kinase 3 beta (GSK3b), which is an inhibitor of glycogen synthase.","Akt (protein kinase B) is activated by insulin and plays a key role in the inactivation of GSK3b.","The insulin signalling cascade promotes glucose storage as glycogen in liver and muscle tissue."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17853"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63903"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T15:22:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T15:23:49+10:30","number":3,"notes":"Simplified stem, improved question wording, expanded explanation for clarity, and added a third learning point about insulin\u0027s role in glucose storage. Used Australian English spelling throughout.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-11T15:23:15+10:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-10567-3.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250930%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250930T095142Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=6995f43270cd643074b62adf6dfcec19a2427d5f5ea32c0c1304f66df4cf1611"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10567"}},